As I mentioned yesterday, the donor must be age 70-1/2 or older at the time of the QCD. How your tool confirms it is up to you. It could compute age after entering the DoB, it could ask if the taxpayer is older than age 70-1/2, etc.

There is currently a $111K annual dollar limit on QCDs.

QCDs should be taken before other IRA withdrawals (which is why I do mine first thing in the new year) to avoid possibly making the QCD part of the taxable distribution for the year. See: https://irahelp.com/qcd-timing/
[BTW – Ed Slott is a nationally recognized expert on IRAs]

An important thing to note is that the 1099-R from your custodian does not specifically identify the amount of your QCD. If you simply enter every field on the 1099-R into your tax software, it will not make an adjustment to your income equal to the amount of the QCD. It is incumbent upon the taxpayer to correctly complete the 1099-R worksheet in their tax software so that the “QCD” appears as an adjustment to income on Form 1040.  Most tax software includes a worksheet that allows the user to indicate if some or all of the IRA distribution is a QCD.


