I may have mentioned this before, but if the taxpayer has both “pre-tax” and “after-tax” money in one or more IRAs, Roth conversions must be made “pro-rata.”

Example:  Taxpayer’s IRA balance at the time of conversion is $175K as follows:
Taxpayer has $50K in pre-tax (deductible) IRA contributions.
Taxpayer has $100K in after-tax (non-deductible) IRA contributions (also referred to as “basis in the IRA”).
Earnings of $25K.

Taxpayer wants to convert $40K to Roth.

Following the pro-rata rule:
The taxable part of the conversion will be [($50K+$25K)/$175K]*$40K = $17.14K
The non-taxable part of the conversion will be ($100K/$175K)*$40K = $22.86K
The taxpayer’s basis in the IRA after conversion is ($100K – 22.86K) = $77.14K

The English language explanation of the above:
Step 1 computes the taxable part based on the amount of the IRA that has never been taxed divided by the IRA value, then multiplied by the amount to be converted.
Step 2 computes the non-taxable part based on the amount of the IRA that has already been taxed (that is, after-tax contributions) divided by the IRA value, then multiplied by the amount to be converted.
Step 3 computes the remaining basis in the IRA by subtracting the amount calculated in step 2 from the original $100K of after-tax contributions.
